Great service, BUT we left a bit disappointed with some aspects of the food quality. We ordered the 3 course Peking duck meal and an order of Chilean sea bass...two most expensive meals. The Peking duck  meal starts out great....they slice the duck skin off table side and serve with Chinese bread wraps like mini burritos  - yum! But then the duck disappears to the kitchen, supposedly to prepare the next two courses, a soup and sliced duck with brocolli.  However, the soup, okay tasting, is more of a beef broth and mushroom soup (couldn't find more than a sliver of meat - not sure it was duck), not duck soup.  The 3rd course, sliced/chopped duck was disappointing- a bit dry since all the meat is served off the bone with absolutely no skin or fat, and the meat doesn't really look like it came from the duck that came to our table. Switched in the kitchen? Also, sauce served with the sliced duck (we had it served on the side) tasted Metallic and bitter, mixed with an overly sweet fruity sauce - not good. Finally, the 8oz of seabass seemed to be cooked correctly, but no flavor besides the sauce....was it really Chilean seabass? $32.00 for that plate, there should have been no doubts and be full of flavor. Next time, maybe just have the duck left at the table the entire meal and pass on the the sea bass.

$15 per person minimum, rancid pieces in appetizer, very good service, high prices, why so many 5 stars?: My daughter and I went there for a light meal.  I ordered the Stuffed Lettuce appetizer at $9.95 (kinda pricey) as my main course.  NOTE at bottom of menu says "$15 minimum per person"!  If I had known this, we probably would not have gone there. Anyhow, the two large lettuce leaves were served with a tablespoon of sauce in each and about 8 little flat squares of something like fried pork skin, along with a dish of chopped pork pieces and some green scallions that you place in the lettuce.  The sauce and the pork I found to be overly salted, not unexpected in a Chinese restaurant.  But there was a definite rancid meat taste, and when I removed the fried pork skin pieces, the rancidity went away.  I noted this to the waiter and he apologized but there was no follow-up from the kitchen. The Calamari appetizer (ordered to meet the "minimum") was very good but we didn't care for the strange mustardy sauce. My daughter liked her house Lomein (interestingly priced at $14.95 as are several dishes so don't meet the "minimum") though again I thought it was salty. Service was attentive and quick.  Prices seemed very high. I am very suspicious of all the 5-star reviews as the food and management is not 5-star.  Read them and you will see they do not have substance.

Hsu's Chinese restaurant in downtown Atlanta is simply delightful. I've eaten here on a few occasions when travel has taken me to A-town. Situated within an easy walk of the Marriott Marquis, Westin, Hyatt, and Hilton, it is a perfect place to go for a great meal for travelers or locals alike. The host/hostess has always seated me and my company promptly. The tables await guests with chopsticks and utensils ready to go. The menus are a bit faded and can be hard to read, but that is a testament to the many people who visit this great establishment.  I always start out with the Wonton soup - the dumplings are supple, hearty, and always flavorful. The stock is superb and has a deeper complexity of fresh herbs and savory goodness that no carry-out Chinese restaurant can remotely replicate. As for entrees, there are many great options, though the curry is one of my favorites. It's popping with flavor and a nice dab of heat. That said, my friends and colleagues have shared only praise for their dishes, too. I should note, Hsu's is one of the few Chinese restaurants I've been at that does not overly salt the food. This is a testament to an expert chef and kitchen staff who take the time to bring big flavor without relying on salt.  The atmosphere is quiet, unpretentious, and comfortable. The low lighting makes for an intimate and pleasant setting with abundant wood accents to create an ambiance that can only be described as warm.  Hsu's is one of my favorite places to eat in Atlanta. I encourage you to visit this excellent restaurant and enjoy the atmosphere and cuisine for yourself. I am sure you'll be pleased.
